<div id="nodeDecoration"><div id="headerContent"><h1 id="nodeTitle">2.2 Causative have</h1></div></div>
<div class="iDevice_wrapper FreeTextIdevice" id="id184">
<div class="iDevice emphasis0">
<div id="ta184_85" class="block iDevice_content">
<p>Have + objet + past participle</p>
<p><i>Ex: I have my watch fixed</i></p>
<p>It is used to express the actions we ask someone else to do for us.</p>
<p><i>Ex: She always has her food delivered (someone else brings the food)</i></p>
<p><i>I had my photograph taken for my passport (someone else took the picture)</i></p>
<p>Compare these two sentences:</p>
<p><i>I</i>’<i>m going to have this chair restored (someone else will restore the chair)</i></p>
<p>Usually it’s not necessary to say who did it for us, but it is possible. In that case we should add by + the agent:</p>
<p><i>I</i>’<i>ve just had my hair cut by my sister.</i></p>
<p><i>Susan had her car repaired by a mechanic by her friend Tom.</i></p>
<p>This structure can be used in any tense or form:</p>
<p><i>We</i>’<i>re having our house painted this week</i></p>
<p><i>Jack will be getting his messages sent by e-mail from now on </i></p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
